flowRoot.flowPara: All fields can be left blank to indicate 'unknown' unless otherwise noted.
version 0.1

The organization(s) that this contact is affiliated with, if any. For contacts that are themselves organizations, give a more general org. that they're part of, if any. (e.g. 'Coast Guard'). The idea is to track individual people or organizations (whichever makes more sense as a contact for a particular observation), but still group them into sets. For example, a contact might be for the Boston Coast Guard office, but it would have a 'Coast Guard' affiliation, so that one could easily answer questions like "How many reports did we get from the Coast Guard last year?"

text.tspan: other, self-explanatory fields: phone, email, address, notes

flowRoot.flowPara: A contact is a name of a person or organization, preferably with some way of contacting them.
Note that only one each of phone, email, etc. is given so that contacts just have a primary phone or email to contact them at. Other ones could be noted in the notes field, if necessary.
The contact's name. Appears in lists of contacts.
Is this a person? (i.e. not an organization)

Name(s) given to this particular animal. E.g. “Kingfisher”, “RW #2427”. Separate multiple names with commas. This field is intended as a catch-all for animal identifiers besides the field number (which is stored separately).
The field number assigned to this animal by the stranding network. Left blank for animals with no number. If not blank, the field number must be unique to this animal.

A date when the animal was certainly dead, as determined from the observations of this animal. If you're unsure of an exact date, just put something certainly after it; e.g. if you know it was dead sometime in July of 2008, just put 2008-07-31 (or 2008-08-01). If you're totally unsure, just put the current date. Any animal with a date before today is considered currently dead.
If the sex of this animal is known, fill it in here and it will then be the default for new observations of this animal.

The most specific taxon this animal is known to be. This will be the default taxon for new observations of this animal. This is separate from the taxa listed in observations of it, since the observations may be mistaken or less specific. Taxa are taken from the "Integrated Taxonomic Information System" (see itis.gov).
If this animal is dead, has a partial necropsy ever been performed on it?
If this animal is dead, has a full necropsy ever been performed on it?
If this animal is dead, what (if any) probable cause of mortality has been determined?

A case is has all the data for one incident of one animal (i.e. a single strike of a ship, a single entanglement of an animal in a particular set of gear). Hypothetically the incident has a single datetime and place that it occurs, although that's almost never actually known.
Much of the information on a case is in the set of observations marked as relevant to it. Cases also serve to connect observations with the animals they're of.

Cases that match the definition of 'entanglement' will have additional entanglement-specific fields. Same goes for shipstrikes. Some cases will be neither of those, and will only have the generic case fields.
The animal this case concerns. This is a reference to an animal entry.
Invalid cases don't count towards year-totals.

Please use '<year>-<month>-<day>'. Injuring incidents themselves are rarely observed, so this is a day whose start is definitely before the incident. For entanglements, this is the 'last seen unentangled' date. For shipstrikes this would usually be the date of the last observation without the relevant scar or wound. In those cases were the date of the incident is known, put it here. (You should also add an observation for that day to indicate the actual incident was observed.) For uncertain dates, put a date at the beginning of the range of possible ones, e.g. if you know the animal was seen uninjured in July of 2009, put '2009-07-01'.
Is there a corresponding Office of Law Enforcement investigation?
The gear-analysis-specific case ID.
gear owner's name

A potentially vague date. It can be left totally blank for 'unknown', or just a year can be specified or just a year and month. Of course, a full date can be entered, too.

The location the gear was set is recorded similarly to the location of observations. That is, it includes fields for coordinate and a description, as well as some specification of jurisdiction (e.g. state vs. federal waters), all of which are optional.

The owner's description of what gear they're missing.

flowRoot.flowPara: Anything that would help identify the individual animal or it's species or age or sex, etc. Even if those are specified above, please note what that was on the basis of.
The cases that this observation is relevant to. These are references to case entries.

Check if this observation corresponds to the ‘initial observation’ on a Level A form. If it does, the observation date should correspond to the "date of initial observation" on the Level A, and the condition should correspond to the "condition at initial observation".

Check if this observation corresponds to the ‘level a examination’ on a Level A form. If it does, the observation date should correspond to the date of examination on the Level A, the condition should correspond to the "condition at examination", and the observer should correspond to the "examiner". Note that an observation can be both the ‘initial observation’ and the ‘examination’ (or neither).
Whoever actually saw the animal. This is a reference to a contact entry.

flowRoot.flowPara: Is this an ‘initial observation’ on a Level A?
Is this a ‘Level A Examination’?

When did the observer see it? (Strictly, when did the observation start?) The earliest observation date for a case's observations is the date used for the case itself, e.g. when assigning a case to a year.
Must include at least a year, but month, day, hour, and minute can all be left blank for unknown.

A prose description of the location. If no coordinates were known at the time, this is all the location info we have. Even if we have coordinates, the method by which they were obtained ought to be noted.
Latitude, longitude. Stored in decimal degrees, but the input form supports a variety of formats.
multiple choice: ‘unknown’, ‘land’, ‘state waters’, 'federal waters', 'international waters'

‘land’ is anyplace above mean-low-tide. ‘state waters’ are defined by the Submerged Lands Act (and numerous relevant court cases). Mostly, they extend 3 nm out from shore. The big exceptions are in FL, TX, and PR, and small exceptions are all over the place. ‘federal waters’ includes all the non-state waters within the 'territorial waters' and 'exclusive economic zone' of the U.S., which extends out 200 nm from shore. For the 'territorial waters' and EEZ of other countries, use 'federal waters'.
If on land or in state waters, the state the observation was in. If in federal waters or the U.S. EEZ, give the nearest state. Leave blank if unknown or outside the U.S.
left blank if in international waters
This is who informed us of the observation. Same as observer if this is a firsthand report.
When did we first heard about the observation? Only a year is required (same as observation date and time).

flowRoot.flowPara: The most specific taxon (e.g. a species) the animal is described as. Can be as vague as an order or as specific as a subspecies or just unknown. Taxa are taken from the "Integrated Taxonomic Information System" (see itis.gov).
multiple choice: 'unknown', 'calf', 'juvenile', 'adult'
Note that these are somewhat subjective, and their definitions, if any, certainly depend on the animal's species. In general, ‘pup’ is a synonym for ‘calf’ and ‘sub-adult’ for ‘juvenile’.
The sex of this animal, if known.
The heart of the database: observations.

An observation is a source of data for an animal and a case. It has an observer and date/time and details of how the observations were taken. Note that the observer data may be scanty if this isn't a firsthand report.

If an observation is relevant to an entanglement or shipstrike case, it may have additional fields relevant to only those types of cases. Note that since an observation can be relevant to more than one case, it may have both entanglement and shipstrike fields.
body condition and wounds description
Were there any wounds observed? 'No' means none were observed. 'Yes' means they were. 'Unknown' means we don't known whether any were observed or not.
Was the animal ashore? Pick 'yes' even if it came ashore during the observation.
multiple choice: 'unknown', 'alive', 'dead, carcass condition unknown', 'fresh dead', 'moderate decomposition', 'advanced decomposition', 'skeletal'
carcass condition definitions:
fresh dead: The carcass was in good condition (fresh/edible).
moderate decomposition: The carcass was in fair condition (decomposed, but organs
basically intact).
advanced decomposition: The carcass was in poor condition (advanced decomposition).
skeletal: Carcass was mummified or skeletal remains.
Note the general condition of the animal: is it emaciated, robust, where are there visible parasites, etc. Describe wounds, noting severity and location on the animal.
Were any photos or videos taken?
Were any biopsy samples taken?
Were any genetic samples taken?
Were any tags put on the animal? If so, please note the tag ID's in the narrative.
A complete description of the observation. No limit as to length. Ideally, all the other fields for an observation could be filled from the info in this one.

Unambiguous description of the physical characteristics of gear. E.g. "a green line over attached to a buoy with a black stripe". Avoid trying to guess the gear's function e.g. "6-inch mesh" is better than "fishing net". Describe the way the gear is on the animal in the 'entanglement details' field.
Was the animal anchored?
disentanglement outcome
Where on the animal's body was gear seen or not seen?
Detailed description of how the animal was entangled.
Was gear removed from the animal for later analysis?
If there was a disentanglement attempted, what was the outcome?
